# Prefer bmin over STL containers

In `src/` C++ code, use **bmin** types instead of the matching STL containers/strings.

| Prefer | Avoid |
|---|---|
| `bmin::String` | `std::string` |
| `bmin::DynArray<T>` | `std::vector<T>` |
| `bmin::Map<K, V>` | `std::map` / `std::unordered_map` |

## Rules

- New and edited code must not introduce `std::string`, `std::vector`, `std::map`, or `std::unordered_map` when a bmin equivalent exists.
- Include the bmin headers you need (e.g. `"bmin/String.h"`, `"bmin/DynArray.h"`, `"bmin/Map.h"`).
- Prefer `bmin::String` / `std::string_view` interop helpers (`bmin/StringInterop.h`) over converting to `std::string`.
- `std::optional`, `std::unique_ptr` / `bmin::UniquePtr`, and other non-container STL utilities remain fine when already used by the codebase.
- Third-party / sdl2w APIs that require STL types are an exception at the boundary only — convert at the edge, keep bmin inside game/model/ui code.

## Examples

```cpp
// BAD
std::vector<int> layerKeys;
std::string name = "world";
std::unordered_map<int, Tile> tiles;

// GOOD
bmin::DynArray<int> layerKeys;
bmin::String name = "world";
bmin::Map<int, Tile> tiles;
```
